\begin_layout Standard
My own experience with religion has not been too religious.
 As you know, Indian traditions in the North are neither obligatory nor
 ideological.
 In fact I only got exposed to some religious literature because my school
 in Varanasi was an old institution established by a Fabian Socialist from
 the 19th century called Annie Besant.
 She had been active in an organisation called Theosophical Society at the
 time.
 The society gathered a lot of ideas from many mystical traditions (including
 Vishnu-Puranas and Tibetan Buddhism) and influenced a lot many people in
 the early 20th century (J Krishamurthy was initially a member).
 While the influence of society was largely gone when I was in school, it
 was hard not be curious about her saintly status in the school.
 Long story short, my readings of religious texts have been mostly investigative
 but I do find that perspectives/tradition shape the world we observe.
\end_layout

